Healthcare-Intervention-ROI-model

Pattaraporn Chutipongvivet

2025-04-23

Executive Summary

Diabetes presents a significant cost burden to insurers, with an average claim of $12,022* per patient annually. By applying machine learning models to early identify high-risk individuals, insurers can intervene proactively reducing claim severity, improving patient outcomes, and boosting ROI.

We evaluated six ML models and one ensemble (stacked) model using performance and financial metrics. The stacked model emerged as the best strategy for maximizing per-member savings while maintaining high sensitivity.

Business Impact: The stacked model can save up to $1,294.30 per person and deliver an ROI of 1438% through targeted interventions.

Key recommendations: - Deploy a predictive model to identify high-risk individuals early. - Prioritize outreach to true positives to reduce long-term claims. - Reinvest part of savings in patient education and tech integration.

This model offers a scalable, cost-effective solution for insurers facing rising chronic disease costs.

  • Reference : https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37909353/

Introduction

This project applies predictive modeling to forecast diabetes risk and quantify financial impact. We focus on enabling targeted preventive action to reduce insurer claim liabilities.

We imported and reviewed the diabetes dataset, ensuring it was ready for modeling. Summary statistics confirm balanced variable types and clean formatting.

Optimizing Intervention Cost vs.Claim Payout

After reviewing the dataset, we found no missing values or anomalies requiring cleaning. Therefore, we proceeded directly to data scaling.

Scale Data

Lets scale the data since there is a difference between how certain variables are recorded. For example, pregnancies are all below 20 while blood pressure can range up to 122. Scaling this ensures faster and more stable fitting.

scaled_predictors <- scale(diabetes[, names(diabetes) != "Outcome"])
diabetes_scaled <- data.frame(scaled_predictors, Outcome = diabetes$Outcome)
summary(diabetes_scaled)

Split

This dataset is large enough to allow a 50-50 train-test split. To maintain class balance, we applied stratified sampling to preserve the proportion of outcome values across both sets.

set.seed(12345)
train_index <- createDataPartition(diabetes_scaled$Outcome, p = 0.5, list = FALSE)

diabetes_train <- diabetes_scaled[train_index, ]
diabetes_test <- diabetes_scaled[-train_index, ]

prop.table(table(diabetes_train$Outcome))
## 
##         0         1 
## 0.6484375 0.3515625
prop.table(table(diabetes_test$Outcome))
## 
##         0         1 
## 0.6536458 0.3463542

Logistic Regression

Logistic regression provided a baseline performance with balanced sensitivity and specificity. While interpretable, it lacked the savings potential of more advanced models.

set.seed(12345)
test_rows <- sample(1:nrow(diabetes),0.5*nrow(diabetes))

DMLR <- glm(Outcome~., data=diabetes_train, family="binomial")

Decision Tree

The decision tree achieved strong interpretability and moderate accuracy. However, it underperformed in financial metrics compared to ensemble approaches.

library(C50)

# Train the decision tree
tree_model <- C5.0(as.factor(Outcome) ~ ., data = diabetes_train)

plot(tree_model)

### DT Prediction

tree_prob <- predict(tree_model, diabetes_test, type = "prob")[, 2]
tree_pred <- ifelse(tree_prob > 0.5, "1", "0")

Random Forest

Random forest improved overall accuracy and stability via aggregation of multiple decision trees. Its performance offered good savings and ROI potential.

diabetesRF <- randomForest(Outcome ~ ., data = diabetes_train)
## Warning in randomForest.default(m, y, ...): The response has five or fewer
## unique values.  Are you sure you want to do regression?
randomForest::varImpPlot(diabetesRF)

RFpred <- predict(diabetesRF, diabetes_test)
RFbin <- ifelse(RFpred >0.5, 1,0)

Support Vector Machine (SVM)

Support Vector Machine delivered solid specificity but lower sensitivity. As a result, fewer high-risk individuals were flagged, limiting cost savings.

svmlinear <- ksvm(as.factor(Outcome) ~., data = diabetes_train, kernal = "linear")

svmpred <- predict(svmlinear, diabetes_test)

The artificial neural network (ANN)

The artificial neural network exhibited signs of overfitting despite tuning. Its low sensitivity resulted in under-detection of true cases.

m1 <- neuralnet(Outcome ~., data = diabetes_train,
                hidden = c(8,4),  #more layers/larger width resulted in lower accuracy - Overfitting
                threshold = 0.005, 
                stepmax = 1e8, 
                lifesign = "full")

Stacked Model

The ensemble stacked model achieved the best performance with high sensitivity and substantial ROI. This makes it the strongest candidate for deployment in real-world insurance applications.

level_two <- data.frame(actual = diabetes_test$Outcome,
  lr = LRpred, 
  DT = tree_pred, 
  RF = RFpred, 
  SVM = svmpred,
  ANN = ANNpred,
  KNN = knn_pred)

lvltwosplit <- sample(1:nrow(level_two),0.3*nrow(level_two))
lvltwo_test <- level_two[lvltwosplit,]
lvltwo_train <- level_two[-lvltwosplit,]

Financial Assumptions

To assess the real-world impact of our models, we translated predictive performance into financial savings using the following key assumptions grounded in industry standards (CDC & ADA estimates):

$90 per intervention This is the estimated cost to proactively engage identified high-risk individuals through reminders and fasting blood glucose testing. This cost applies to everyone predicted as positive (i.e., both true positives and false positives).

$12,022 annual diabetes-related cost per patient This represents the expected annual medical expenses for individuals with unmanaged diabetes, based on American Diabetes Association (ADA) estimates.

35% reduction in claim cost for correctly flagged patients (true positives) When an at-risk patient is correctly identified and receives early intervention, their claim cost is reduced by 35%. This reflects improved health outcomes and fewer complications, as supported by CDC and ADA.

intervention_cost_per_person <- 90       # Cost for prevention (e.g. checkup + test)
annual_claim_cost <- 12022               # Cost per diabetes case annually
claim_reduction_rate <- 0.35             # Estimated savings from early intervention (TP only)

Financial Impact

Stacked modeling reduced average claims and improved per-person savings. The total projected savings demonstrate clear cost-efficiency versus the no-intervention baseline.

# From confusionMatrix on stacked model
TN <- 36
FP <- 39
FN <- 3
TP <- 37
total_insured <- TN + FP + FN + TP


# 1. Total intervention cost (applies to everyone predicted as positive: TP + FP)
intervention_cost <- (TP + FP) * intervention_cost_per_person

# 2. Adjusted claim cost: 
# - FN = untreated diabetics = full cost
# - TP = treated = only 65% of full cost (due to 35% reduction)
claim_cost <- (FN * annual_claim_cost) + (TP * (1 - claim_reduction_rate) * annual_claim_cost)

# 3. Total cost = intervention + claim cost
total_cost <- intervention_cost + claim_cost

# 4. "Would have paid" = if no intervention, just full cost of (TP + FN)
no_intervention_cost <- (TP + FN) * annual_claim_cost

# 5. Savings = baseline - new cost
savings <- no_intervention_cost - total_cost

# 6. Savings per person
savings_per_person <- savings / total_insured

# 7. ROI = savings per person / intervention cost per person
roi <- savings_per_person / intervention_cost_per_person

Business Roadmap

To implement predictive modeling for diabetes prevention in an insurance context, we propose the following roadmap:

  1. Model Integration
    • Embed the stacked model into underwriting or care management systems.
    • Automate scoring of new applicants and existing policyholders.
  2. Preventive Outreach Program
    • Trigger interventions (e.g., tests, lifestyle coaching) for high-risk individuals (predicted as positive).
    • Monitor compliance and health outcomes via patient portals.
  3. Reinvestment Strategy
    • Use part of cost savings to fund:
      • Health education initiatives.
      • Training programs for primary care providers.
      • Community partnerships for lifestyle improvement.
  4. Monitoring & Optimization
    • Track KPIs: intervention uptake, TP/FN rate, claim reductions.
    • Recalibrate model quarterly using new data and performance feedback.
  5. Reinsurance
    • Any high risk policies can be reinsured to ensure a balanced risk management portfolio

This roadmap ensures not only prediction but action and accountability, turning insights into measurable business impact.

Recommendation

Based on both predictive performance and financial outcomes, we recommend deploying the stacked ensemble model as the predictive engine for early diabetes detection programs.

This model achieved: - Highest sensitivity (92.5%), ensuring most at-risk individuals are captured. - Strongest ROI (1438%), offering the best return on preventive care investments. - Most cost savings ($1,294.30/person), outperforming traditional single-model approaches.

Next Steps: - Integrate the stacked model into a pilot insurance product. - Automate the scoring pipeline for ongoing use. - Track real-world intervention outcomes and refine the model quarterly.

Conclusion

By leveraging a stacked machine learning approach, insurers can unlock a new ROI frontier combining predictive analytics with targeted preventive care.

This strategy can reduce diabetes-related claims by over 30%, yielding up to $1,294 in savings per member annually. Beyond financial impact, it positions insurers as proactive health partners enhancing member satisfaction, loyalty, and long-term cost control.
